lenders.name: Evan
lenders.occupational_info:
EH Demolition, LLC

 

1.0 Executive Summary

 

    As Greater Cincinnati experiences renewed interest, with emphasis on its historic building stock, there is a growing demand for interior demolition. EH Demolition, LLC will tap into this demand with a focus on fast, efficient, and affordable services that will “Clear the Way” for customers.

 

1.1  Objectives

 

1.      Raise $10,500 in investor income to purchase necessary equipment and marketing tools, and maintain initial overhead costs.

2.      Establish and maintain relationships with local general contractors with an emphasis on those who specialize in historic buildings.

3.      Maintain quality employee pool by offering consistent work for fair pay.

4.      Generate $150,000 in gross sales by July 2017, with an eye on further gains.

 

1.2  Mission

 

1.      EH Demolition, LLC is devoted to fast, efficient and affordable demolition services that will “Clear the Way” for building owners to achieve their renovation goals.

 

1.3 Key To Success

 

1.      Establish and maintain relationships with general contractors through an aggressive marketing strategy coupled with high quality work.

2.      Differentiate ourselves from larger companies and other smaller ones by demonstrating fast, efficient and affordable work.

3.      Build up strong and reliable employees through fair treatment and pay.


2.0 Company Summary


   EH Demolition, LLC will be a small interior demolition company with the owner acting as sales representative and liaison between clients and employees. It will build its reputation by providing quality work with an emphasis on efficiency and client engagement.


2.2 Competitive Comparison


    With roughly 100 alteration permits applied for daily in the City of Cincinnati in 2015 there is a high demand for quality contractors. Currently in the interior demolition field there are larger companies such as Sherwin Williams and HGC that offer demolition along with overall renovation services. As more smaller investors are buying historic building stock in Cincinnati they are left at a disadvantage using these companies due to their wishing to contract out the entire job. Currently the main competitor EH Demolition, LLC would face would be a company named Second Chance Demolition, LLC. This company is run by an individual who has lost contracts with companies like Bair Properties in recent months due to quality of work and client engagement. They currently still do work with 3CDC, who often use smaller companies for their projects. With multiple historic preservation projects coming online in the coming months, we would be at an advantage to begin marketing to groups such as 3CDC, Model Group, Bair Properties, Cornerstone, Urban Sites, Urban Expansion, and the multiple smaller independent real estate investors working in Cincinnati’s “core” neighborhoods. Being “the only game in town” will no longer be an advantage to Second Chance. The appearance of a new, smaller company with an emphasis on client service will be a welcomed asset to the Cincinnati redevelopment community.


2.3 Pricing Projects


1. From a labor standpoint our goal would be to have independent contractors work for EH Demolition, LLC on a "per job" basis. This compensation would be based off of expected completion time and would ideally come out to a $14.00 an hour rate. We would emphasize to our employees that this "per hour" rate could be higher should they complete work ahead of schedule. This added incentive would ensure that our work would be done on an efficient basis, as well as help foster employee loyalty. The average starting rate for a demolition laborer in the Greater Cincinnati area is $10.00 an hour and has resulted in laborers working at a slower pace to ensure more hours. With our model we would help eliminate this problem while also offering a higher return for their productivity.

 2. Based on this model of employee pay we would be able to offer competitive bids for each project based off of the size and labor needs. Our pricing model would include the cost of labor as well as insurance and profit. We would ask the client to bear the cost of the hauling and permits for blocking parking. With our emphasis on having the job done efficiently we could very well become the lowest bidders in the area without skimping on profit.

3. Example: John Doe wants to clear out his 3 story, 8 unit building (including drop ceilings, framing and drywall, bathtubs and toilets) to create a 3 story single family unit. With 3 laborers the demolition part of this job Should take 1 week, with an additional week of hauling. With insurance averaging $2,500 a month and the set labor cost for this job totaling $3,360, we could bid this job at $8,500 and remain competitive and profitable. (A job of this size was bid by Second Chance Demolition for $10,000).


2.4 Capital Needed


     To begin to cut into this market share EH Demolition, LLC will need to raise $10,500 in investor income for the following needs:

Equiptment (Sledge Hammers, Pry Bars, Safety Gear, etc): $800.

Marketing tools (Business cards, Banners, T-Shirts, Graphic Designer): $650.

Initial Overhead (Employee Compensation, Liability and Workers Comp Insurance): $9,050
